{
  "q1_accurate": [
    {"tool": "sense_search", "query": "storage database handle Storage struct", "note": "pinned storage.Storage at internal/storage/storage.go:13 and NewStorage at :18 in one call, which anchored the whole audit"},
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "storage.Storage", "note": "the composed_by list gave me 14 retaining structs with exact refs — api/api.go:13, api/middleware.go:16, fever/handler.go:27, googlereader/handler.go:68, googlereader/middleware.go:21, metric/metric.go:146, reader/icon/checker.go:16, reader/opml/handler.go:16, storage/certificate_cache.go:18, storage/entry_query_builder.go:20, ui/auth_proxy_middleware.go:17, ui/handler.go:15, ui/web_session_middleware.go:18, worker/worker.go:18. Every one of those appears in my final answer"},
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "storage.Storage", "note": "affected_via_composition restated the same 14 holders and direct_callers_by_area gave the per-area counts I used to structure the grouping; also surfaced the closure retainers indirectly via fever.Middleware and server.newReadinessProbe in called_by"},
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "worker.Pool", "note": "correctly showed Pool composes only model.Job — that negative result let me state that worker.Pool does NOT retain the handle, only worker.worker does"}
  ],
  "q1_wrong": [
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "storage.Storage", "note": "composed_by is typed on *storage.Storage only, so it missed the three in-package builders that copy the raw *sql.DB out of Storage — batchBuilder (batch.go:18), feedQueryBuilder (feed_query_builder.go:19), entryPaginationBuilder (entry_pagination_builder.go:19). These are the sharpest stale-handle risk in the ticket and I only found them by grepping for '*sql.DB' fields"},
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "storage.Storage", "note": "completeness verdict 'partial' with 101 hidden of 211 affected — for an audit whose failure mode is a missed holder, a partial verdict meant I could not treat the list as closed and had to grep-verify"}
  ],
  "q2_fallbacks": [
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "storage.Storage", "fallback": "grep", "missing": "no way to ask 'what retains the underlying *sql.DB' — composition is tracked per-type, so the handle laundered through s.db into batchBuilder/feedQueryBuilder/entryPaginationBuilder was invisible. Grep for '\\*sql.DB' in internal/ found all four"},
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "storage.Storage", "fallback": "grep", "missing": "closure and goroutine capture. fever.Middleware and server.newReadinessProbe appeared as plain callers with no signal they return a handler that retains store; cli.feedScheduler/cleanupScheduler retain it in an infinite goroutine frame. I grepped 'store \\*storage.Storage) (func|http\\.)' to find them"},
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query": "storage.Storage", "fallback": "read", "missing": "the composed_by entries give the struct's line range but not the field line or the field name, and no one-line description of the subsystem. The ticket demanded per-holder field:line plus a phrase on what it does, so I read internal/storage/*.go, worker/worker.go, worker/pool.go, metric/metric.go, cli/scheduler.go and the ui/api/fever/googlereader struct blocks to get field lines and purpose"},
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query": "storage.Storage", "fallback": "grep", "missing": "construction sites. I wanted the 'built at' line for each holder (api/api.go:21, fever/handler.go:23, worker/pool.go:40, http/server/server.go:147) and grepped 'store: *store|storage: *storage' plus NewCertificateCache to get them"}
  ],
  "q3_hints": [
    {"tool": "sense_search", "query_before": "storage database handle Storage struct", "query_after": "sense_graph on storage.Storage", "hint": "next_steps: 'strong match — explore its relationships' with args {symbol: storage.Storage} — I took the suggested symbol verbatim as my graph query"},
    {"tool": "sense_graph", "query_before": "storage.Storage", "query_after": "grep for '\\*storage.Storage' and '\\*sql.DB' fields excluding _test", "hint": "index_caveat: 'Static graph may miss: method-on-field dispatch (c.engine.X), function-value passing (handlers stored as fields)' — function-value passing is exactly the closure-retention case in this ticket, so I ran the literal greps instead of shipping the 14-holder list as complete"},
    {"tool": "sense_blast", "query_before": "storage.Storage", "query_after": "grep verification of holder list", "hint": "completeness verdict 'partial', resolved 110, hidden 101 — for an exhaustive audit I could not accept a partial set, so I cross-checked with grep rather than issuing more narrowed Sense queries"}
  ],
  "q4_value": "The composed_by / affected_via_composition edge on storage.Storage — 14 retaining structs across 8 packages with exact refs, returned in one call. That is precisely the retention question the ticket asked, and reconstructing it with grep would have required me to already know the field name and type spelling in each package; instead I got the list first and used grep only to confirm it.",
  "q5_improve": "Track retention through field extraction, not just field type. When a constructor does `&batchBuilder{db: s.db}`, that builder retains storage.Storage's handle transitively — surface it as a second-order composed_by entry (with the field line, not just the struct line) and flag closures that capture a param and outlive the call. Those two gaps were 7 of my 21 holders and every one of my grep fallbacks.",
  "score": 8,
  "score_rationale": "The composed_by edge gave me 14 cross-package retainers with citable refs in a single call — the transitive-holder view grep cannot produce without knowing every field spelling in advance (Q1) — but its own index_caveat about function-value passing plus a 'partial' completeness verdict correctly told me the set was not closed, and grep then found 7 more holders it structurally could not see (Q2), which is squarely the 7-8 'faster, but still needed fallbacks' band rather than 9-10."
}

